[1] Albania, poultry: control measures
Date: Fri, 10 Mar 2006
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Reuters alertnet, 9 Mar 2006 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L09628210.htm>

Albania planned to cull and bury nearly 2000
chickens in the southern Sarande area on Thursday
[9 Mar 2006] after a chicken was found to have
died from the deadly H5N1 strain of bird flu,
officials said.
Albania's first case of the virus was confirmed
on Wednesday [8 Mar 2006]. It was found 20 km (12
miles) north of the border with Greece, close to
the Butrint lagoon, a known resting ground for
migratory birds.
Veterinary teams clad in white protective suits
swooped in on the area, wringing the necks of
fluttering chickens, then putting them in black
garbage bags. One vet said they shoved live
chickens in the bags to suffocate them.
"The villagers themselves are bringing their
chickens in plastic bags," Agriculture Ministry
spokesman Rexhep Shahu told Reuters. "We are
culling them as a preventive measure and we will
be monitoring the situation for 30 days."
Some villagers asked to keep their backyard
poultry. "Let me eat it, I don't care if I do
die," said one elderly lady.
"The Minister has been saying it's safe to eat,
so we have eaten them," added a man. "We didn't
eat the last 4 we had left because we're
observing Lent (for Orthodox Easter)".
Villagers were to get 700 leks (6.80 USD) for a
grown chicken and 400 leks (3.90 USD) for a
chick. Medical teams took blood samples to see if
any villagers were infected.
The bird flu virus has spread rapidly since the
beginning of February 2006, and is now present in
most European countries. It has infected 176
people worldwide, killing 96 since 2003.
Scientists fear it is only a matter of time
before it mutates into a form that passes easily
among people, triggering a pandemic.
--
