[2] Germany, stone marten: WHO update
Date: Fri, 10 Mar 2006
From: Marianne Hopp <mjhopp12@yahoo.com>
Source: WHO Epidemic and Pandemic Alert and Response (EPR), 9 Mar 2006 [edited]
<http://www.who.int/csr/don/2006_03_09a/en/index.html>

Officials in Germany have today confirmed H5N1
infection in a 2nd mammalian species, the stone
marten. This finding marks the first documented
infection of this species with an avian influenza
virus. Previously, H5N1 infection was confirmed
in Germany in 3 domestic cats.
The marten was found alive, but showing signs of
severe illness, on the Baltic island of Ruegen on
2 Mar 2006. The animal was euthanized. Tests
conducted at Germany's
Friedrich-Loeffler-Institut for Animal Health
confirmed infection with the H5N1 avian influenza
virus.
The ill animal was found in the same heavily
affected area of the island, near Schaprode, as 3
dead domestic cats. Tests conducted at the
Friedrich-Loeffler-Institut subsequently
confirmed that all 3 cats were infected with the
highly pathogenic H5N1 virus. The stone marten is
a predatory nocturnal mammal with feeding habits
similar to those of domestic cats. As with the
cats found on Ruegen island, the marten is
presumed to have acquired its infection after
feeding on an infected bird.
Since 16 Feb 2006, German authorities have
confirmed H5N1 infection in 125 wild swans,
ducks, geese, and birds of prey on Ruegen Island,
pointing to considerable opportunities for
exposures in small mammals that feed on birds.
As is the case with humans, infections in animal
species other than birds are rare. To date, only
domestic poultry are known to have played a role
in the transmission cycle of the virus from
animals to humans.
In July 2005, tests on 3 rare Owston's palm
civets that died in captivity in Viet Nam
detected H5N1 infection, marking the first known
infection in this mammalian species [see
20051029.3160]. Large cats, including tigers and
leopards, kept in [captivity] and fed on infected
poultry carcasses, have also been infected and
developed severe disease. Ferrets are another
mammalian species known to be susceptible to
infection.
Further investigation is needed to determine
whether evidence of H5N1 infection in new
mammalian species has any significance for the
risk of human infection or the potential of this
virus to adapt to mammals, including humans.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The above WHO update adds some
clinico-epidemiological information to the
initial posting on the infected stone marten. In
a separate Reuters' newswire, it was indicated
that the animal was caught alive and later put
down. In Germany, as elsewhere, those engaged in
wildlife protection and conservation are
instructed to apply the required precautionary
measures when handling the captured/treated
animals, to avoid risk of infection. Defra's
Protocol for the collection and submission of
samples, including public health advice, might
serve as a useful guideline:
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/animalh/diseases/notifiable/disease/ai/wildbirds/surveillance.htm>.
See also the following subscriber's comment. - Mod.AS]
