[5] H5N1 influenza time-line: WHO update
Date: Fri, 10 Mar 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: WHO EPR web-site, Avian influenza, accessed 10 Mar 2005 [edited]
<http://www.who.int/csr/disease/avian_influenza/Timeline_3_03.pdf>

[In posting 20051029.3160, we presented a
chronological list summarising the main
animal-health related events since the beginning
of the H5N1 panzootic and the relevant research
covering the period from 1996 ("Highly pathogenic
H5N1 virus is isolated from a farmed goose in
Guangdong Province, China") to 26 Oct 2005
("Croatia confirms H5N1 in wild birds"). The list
was copied, with some editorial modifications,
from the WHO influenza home page. It included 47
updates. We hereby copy the continuation of the
said time-line list, covering the subsequent 21
updates up to the last available one, dated 3 Mar
2006, and one research paper of significance,
published during the covered period. - Mod.AS]
H5N1 influenza time-line: Nov 2005 -- 3 Mar 2006
------------------------------------------------
48. 29 Nov 2005: China reports more fresh
outbreaks in poultry. Since mid-October, 25
outbreaks have been detected in 9 provinces,
resulting in the culling of around 20 million
birds.
49. 5 Dec 05: Ukraine reports its first H5N1 outbreak in domestic birds.
50. 11 Nov 05: Kuwait detects highly pathogenic
H5N1 in a single migratory flamingo, marking the
first report of this disease in the Gulf region.
51. 27 Dec 05: Turkey reports a fresh outbreak
in the eastern province of Igdir.
52. 23 Jan 06: Turkey reports poultry outbreaks
in 11 of the country's 81 provinces.
53. 2 Feb 06: Iraq reports its first outbreak of
H5N1, in backyard flocks in same province where
human case detected.
54. 8 Feb 06: Nigeria confirms H5N1 in chickens
-- the first detection of this virus in Africa.
55. 9 Feb 06: Azerbaijan confirms H5N1 in migratory birds.
56. 11 Feb 06: Bulgaria, Greece, and Italy confirm H5N1 in wild birds (swans).
57. 12 Feb 06: Slovenia confirms H5N1 in a wild bird (swan).
58. 13 Feb 06: Russia reports the first H5N1
outbreaks (at large commercial farms) in its
Caucasus region, near the border with Azerbaijan.
More than half a million birds are destroyed.
59. 14 Feb 06: Iran, Austria and Germany confirms H5N1 in wild birds (swans).
60. 17 Feb 06: Egypt confirms H5N1 in domestic poultry.
61. 18 Feb 06: India confirms H5N1 in domestic poultry.
62. 19 Feb 06: France confirms H5N1 in a wild duck.
63. 21 Feb 06: Hungary confirms H5N1 in wild birds (swans).
- Malaysia confirms H5N1 in a flock of free-range
poultry, marking a return of the disease. The
country had been considered disease-free since
Jan 05.
64. 25 Feb 06: Slovakia and Bosnia-Herzegovina
confirm H5N1 in wild birds (swans).
- France confirms H5N1 in farmed turkeys, marking
the first appearance of this disease in domestic
poultry in the EU.
65. 27 Feb 06: Georgia confirms H5N1 in wild birds (swans).
- Niger confirms H5N1 in domestic poultry.
66. 28 Feb 06: Sweden reports H5 in wild birds (ducks).
- Germany confirms H5N1 infection in a dead domestic cat.
67. 1 March 06: Switzerland confirms H5N1 in a wild bird (duck).
68. 2 March 06: Serbia-Montenegro reports H5 in a wild bird (swan).
Research:
Chen H et al. Establishment of multiple
sublineages of H5N1 influenza virus in Asia:
implications for pandemic control. Proc Natl Acad
Sci USA 2006; 103: 2845�2850.
Studies of H5N1 viruses show that multiple
genetically and antigenically distinct
sublineages of the virus are now established in
poultry in parts of Asia. Poultry-to-poultry
transmission is thought to sustain endemicity of
the virus in this region. H5N1 virus is isolated
from apparently healthy migratory birds in
southern China, suggesting that migratory birds
can carry the virus over long distances.
--
